However, Cloudbeat only supports Linux and Kubernetes. While it‚Äôs true that the same agent policy may include other integrations supporting these operating systems, it doesn‚Äôt make sense to propose these options after our integration installation. fix: Critical architectural flaw - registry-agnostic provenance authentication

üö® CRITICAL ISSUE FIXED:
- Build step was registry-agnostic but provenance was GitHub-only
- Caused silent failures: containers built but NO SLSA provenance generated
- False promise: 'Universal workflow' that only worked completely with GitHub

‚ùå Previous Broken Pattern:
- Build: ‚úÖ Any registry (docker.io, quay.io, ECR, etc.)
- Provenance: ‚ùå Hardcoded GitHub credentials only
- Result: Containers without attestations for non-GitHub registries

‚úÖ Fixed Architecture:
- Build: ‚úÖ Any registry with correct credentials
- Provenance: ‚úÖ Dynamic credentials based on target registry
- Result: Complete SLSA Level 3 provenance for ANY registry

üîß Technical Solution:
- Dynamic registry credential detection
- Registry-specific username/password mapping
- Proper error handling for missing credentials
- True registry-agnostic provenance generation

üåç Now Works Completely With:
- GitHub Container Registry: github.actor + GITHUB_TOKEN
- Docker Hub: DOCKER_USERNAME + DOCKER_PASSWORD secrets
- Quay.io: REGISTRY_USERNAME + REGISTRY_PASSWORD secrets
- AWS ECR: REGISTRY_USERNAME + REGISTRY_PASSWORD secrets
- Any registry: REGISTRY_USERNAME + REGISTRY_PASSWORD secrets

üéØ Result: True universal container workflow with complete SLSA provenance for ANY registry

pull_request.title: fix: Resolve Firebase deployment error and income miscategorization
pull_request.body:
This commit addresses two critical issues: a failing Firebase deployment workflow and the miscategorization of personal income.

- **Firebase Deployment**: The `.github/workflows/firebase-hosting-deploy.yml` file has been corrected with the proper `projectId` and `firebaseServiceAccount` secret name, resolving the deployment error. The `package.json` has also been updated to include a `build` script as expected by the workflow.

- **Income Categorization**: New, high-priority rules have been added to `CategoryManager.js` to correctly identify transfers from the main sweep account (0111) to Lisa's personal accounts (0898, 0005) as "Personal Income - Lisa's Income". A new account mapping for account `0005` was also added to `AppConfig.js`.

- **Dashboard Date Range**: The `MonthlyDashboard.js` date filter has been corrected to ensure it displays the user's historical data from April-July 2025.

- **Data Recovery**: A `fixLisaIncomeTransactions` utility function has been added to `index.html` to allow for the easy re-categorization of any historical transactions that were previously miscategorized.

pull_request.title: fix: Register driver post initialization
pull_request.body:
On my machine (Resonite 2025.6.17.855, ResoniteModLoader 3.0.0), VRCFTReceiver would be loaded by ResoniteModLoader immediately before Resonite initialized the input interface. This caused the driver initialization function to silently fail.

This fix defers driver initialization until after Resonite is fully initialized. The [ResoniteModLoader wiki](https://github.com/resonite-modding-group/ResoniteModLoader/wiki/Creating-Mods#runpostinit) states that the input device setup occurs after `OnEngineInit` and that `Engine.RunPostInit` should be used to register a callback instead.

This change also improves error logging during startup for other unexpected null conditions within FrooxEngine.Engine.

With this fix I was able to get blinking working, but not full eye tracking yet.

> - Created comprehensive test suite to validate CI configuration, package dependencies, and workflow syntax
> - Enhanced error detection to catch configuration issues early in the CI pipeline
